issues.title: Crankshaft Position Sensor Failure
issues.description: The crankshaft position sensor frequently fails on NB Miatas, causing intermittent stalling, rough idle, and no-start conditions. This is a common issue across all NB model years.
issues.fix_description: Replace the crankshaft position sensor located behind the crankshaft pulley. Requires removal of the pulley and timing belt covers.
issues.prevention: Regular maintenance and replacing the sensor proactively around 80,000-100,000 miles

issues.title: Rear Main Seal Oil Leak
issues.description: The rear main seal commonly develops leaks, particularly on higher mileage vehicles. Oil leaks onto the clutch and flywheel area, potentially contaminating the clutch disc.
symptoms: oil leak at rear of engine
issues.fix_description: Engine or transmission must be removed to access and replace the rear main seal. Often done during clutch replacement.
issues.prevention: Use quality oil, maintain proper oil change intervals, avoid over-revving

issues.title: Power Window Regulator Failure
issues.description: Window regulators, particularly on the driver's side, commonly fail causing windows to drop into the door or bind while operating. The plastic guides and cables wear out over time.
issues.fix_description: Replace window regulator assembly. Door panel must be removed for access. Often includes new window guides.
issues.prevention: Avoid forcing windows, lubricate tracks periodically, support window when door panel is removed

issues.title: Soft Top Frame Cracking
issues.description: The convertible soft top frame, particularly the rear bow sections, can develop stress cracks over time. This is especially common on cars with frequent top operation.
issues.fix_description: Weld cracks or replace damaged frame sections. May require complete frame replacement in severe cases.
issues.prevention: Regular lubrication of pivot points, gentle operation, avoid forcing top mechanism

issues.title: Mass Air Flow Sensor Contamination
issues.description: The MAF sensor becomes contaminated with oil and debris over time, causing poor idle, hesitation, and reduced performance. Common on all NB years.
issues.fix_description: Clean MAF sensor with appropriate cleaner or replace if cleaning doesn't resolve the issue. Check for intake leaks.
issues.prevention: Regular air filter replacement, use quality air filters, avoid over-oiling aftermarket air filters

issues.title: Clutch Slave Cylinder Failure
issues.description: The clutch slave cylinder commonly fails, causing clutch pedal to go to the floor and inability to shift gears. Internal seals deteriorate over time.
issues.fix_description: Replace clutch slave cylinder and bleed hydraulic system. Often replaced with master cylinder as a pair.
issues.prevention: Regular brake/clutch fluid changes, avoid riding the clutch pedal

issues.title: Ignition Coil Pack Failure
issues.description: Individual ignition coils in the coil pack commonly fail, causing misfires, rough running, and reduced performance. More common on 2001-2005 models with individual coils.
issues.fix_description: Replace failed ignition coil(s) and spark plugs. Diagnose with OBD scanner to identify specific cylinder.
issues.prevention: Replace spark plugs at recommended intervals, use quality ignition components

issues.title: Cooling System Thermostat Failure
issues.description: Thermostats commonly stick closed or fail to open properly, causing overheating issues. This can lead to engine damage if not addressed promptly.
issues.fix_description: Replace thermostat and gasket. Flush cooling system and refill with proper coolant mixture.
issues.prevention: Regular coolant changes, use proper coolant mixture, replace thermostat preventively at 60,000 miles

issues.title: Fuel Tank Evaporative Emissions Issues
issues.description: EVAP system components including the purge solenoid and carbon canister can fail, triggering check engine lights related to emissions. TSB addresses common EVAP codes.
issues.fix_description: Replace faulty EVAP components such as purge solenoid, carbon canister, or vacuum lines based on diagnostic codes.
issues.prevention: Don't top off fuel tank, replace gas cap if damaged, avoid aftermarket modifications to fuel system

issues.title: Door Handle Mechanism Failure
issues.description: Interior and exterior door handles commonly break or become loose due to plastic component wear. The door handle cables can also stretch or break.
issues.fix_description: Replace broken door handle components or cables. Door panel removal required for interior handle repair.
issues.prevention: Gentle operation of door handles, lubricate mechanisms periodically

issues.title: Alternator Bearing Failure
issues.description: Alternator bearings commonly wear out, causing squealing noises and eventual alternator failure. The charging system may become intermittent before complete failure.
issues.fix_description: Replace alternator or rebuild with new bearings. Check belt tension and condition during replacement.
issues.prevention: Regular belt inspections, proper belt tension, replace worn belts promptly

issues.title: Valve Cover Gasket Oil Leak
issues.description: The valve cover gasket commonly develops leaks, causing oil to seep onto the exhaust manifold and create burning oil odors. More common on higher mileage vehicles.
symptoms: oil leak on top of engine
issues.fix_description: Replace valve cover gasket and spark plug tube seals. Clean oil residue from engine components.
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes, avoid over-tightening valve cover bolts, replace gasket preventively during timing belt service

editorial.hero_blurb: The NB Miata represents the perfect evolution of the original formula - more refined than the NA while maintaining every ounce of driving purity. This generation struck the ideal balance between modern amenities and analog connection that makes every drive feel special.
editorial.essence: The NB Miata perfected what the original started, offering a more sophisticated driving experience without losing the raw connection between driver and machine. It's the sweet spot where classic roadster charm meets just enough modern refinement to be truly usable daily.
editorial.heritage: Second-generation Miata building on the NA's revolutionary return of the affordable sports car, refined through lessons learned from the original while staying true to the lightweight rear-wheel-drive roadster mission that revived an entire segment.
editorial.design_philosophy: Evolutionary refinement over revolution - designers focused on improving NVH, interior quality, and structural rigidity while preserving the pure driving dynamics and timeless proportions that made the original so beloved.
editorial.motorsport_history: Dominant force in SCCA autocross and club racing, with factory support in various series. The NB's improved chassis rigidity made it even more capable on track while maintaining the accessible performance that made Spec Miata racing so popular.
editorial.engine_character: The 1.8L BP engine is eager and responsive, with a linear power delivery that rewards revs. It's not about brute force but about staying in the powerband - smooth, willing, and surprisingly torquey for its size with a sweet spot around 5,000 RPM.
editorial.transmission_feel: The 5-speed manual is precise and mechanical, with short throws and positive engagement. Each shift feels deliberate and connected, with a clutch that's light enough for daily driving but communicative enough to feel every launch.
editorial.chassis_dynamics: Beautifully balanced and predictable, with just enough body roll to telegraph what's happening before the limits. The chassis rewards smooth inputs and builds confidence progressively - it's forgiving but always honest about grip levels.
editorial.steering_feel: Perfectly weighted manual rack delivers unfiltered feedback from the front wheels. Quick ratio makes the car feel eager to change direction, while the natural weight builds appropriately with speed - this is how steering should feel.
editorial.brake_confidence: Adequate for the car's performance envelope with good pedal feel and progressive bite. Not designed for serious track work without upgrades, but perfectly matched to the car's sporting intentions on back roads and spirited drives.
editorial.sound_signature: A cultured growl that's more sophisticated than the raw NA - the exhaust note is purposeful without being harsh, while the engine note builds to a satisfying crescendo at higher RPMs without drone at cruise.
editorial.ideal_owner: Driving purists who appreciate mechanical connection and don't need overwhelming power. Perfect for someone who values the journey over straight-line speed and understands that 'slow car fast' can be more rewarding than the opposite.
editorial.not_ideal_for: Those seeking significant cargo space, all-weather capability, or high-speed highway comfort. If you need a practical daily driver or want impressive straight-line performance numbers, look elsewhere.
editorial.buyers_summary: Look for examples with maintenance records and check for rust, especially around the rear wheel wells. The NB is reliable when maintained but benefits from enthusiast ownership - a well-maintained high-mileage car often beats a neglected garage queen.

expertReviews.title: NB Miata ULTIMATE Buyers Guide
pros: Fun, reliable and cheap
Carefree top-down driving experience
NB2 improvements including VVT, better headlights and modernized interior
Special editions offer unique styling and six-speed transmissions
Great daily driver when kept stock
cons: Automatic transmission removes 35% of the fun
Hard tops take away the convertible experience
Slamming the car ruins daily drivability
Some special edition wheels are described as ugly
No crank window option available
expertReviews.verdict: The NB Miata is described as the most 'smiles per miles' car available, offering fun, reliable, and affordable motoring. The reviewer emphasizes keeping it stock for maximum enjoyment, particularly maintaining the convertible top functionality. NB2 models (2001-2005) are recommended over NB1 for better daily usability with improvements like VVT, projector headlights, and modernized interior. Special editions offer unique styling and six-speed transmissions for those wanting something more distinctive.

expertReviews.title: Mazda Miata NB | The Good, The Bad, And The Ugly
pros: Excellent reliability and gas mileage (28 mpg combined)
Outstanding handling like a go-kart
Extensive aftermarket support
Easy to work on and maintain
Inexpensive replacement parts
Great community of owners
Better than NA Miata but cheaper
Will rise in value over time
cons: Very small size with safety concerns
Limited interior and trunk space
No cup holders
Slow acceleration (142 hp)
Convertible top leaks and expensive to replace
Rubber brake lines need replacement
No pop-up headlights like NA
Rear wheel drive only (winter driving)
Sketchy sellers in market
Rusts very quickly
expertReviews.verdict: The NB Miata is praised as better than the NA in every way while being cheaper. Ideal for track use and autocross with go-kart-like handling, excellent reliability, and strong aftermarket support. However, buyers should avoid automatic transmissions and carefully inspect for rust. Best suited for track enthusiasts rather than daily drivers due to size limitations and lack of practicality features.

expertReviews.title: The BEST Mazda Miata That Doesn't Get the Credit It Deserves!
pros: Lightweight at 2300 lbs
Excellent value - $3-5k less than NA Miatas
Fun and nimble handling
Reliable 1.8L engine
Glass rear window vs plastic on first gen
Larger trunk than first generation
Feels quick enough despite modest power
cons: Fixed headlights instead of beloved pop-ups
Very cramped interior especially for taller drivers
Only 140 horsepower
Small everything - controls, instrument cluster
Not suitable for long road trips
Aftermarket steering wheels may not suit everyone
expertReviews.verdict: The NB Miata is the forgotten generation that deserves more credit. Despite losing the pop-up headlights and being slightly heavier, it offers the same fun driving experience as the original at a significantly lower price point. At $5-7k for good examples, it's the most compelling value in the Miata lineup for those seeking lightweight, nimble driving dynamics.

expertReviews.title: The best Mazda MX-5 ever? // Miata NB review
pros: Exceptional driving experience with Jinba Ittai philosophy
Excellent handling and steering feel
Surprisingly comfortable ride quality
Simple and effective soft-top operation
Great value for money at around 1,500
Incredibly small turning circle
Strong enthusiast community and parts availability
More practical than expected with decent boot space
cons: Serious rust issues, especially in structural areas like sills
Not very fast with 110 bhp 1.6L engine taking over 9 seconds 0-60
Struggles on hills and requires pushing the engine hard
Wind noise with roof down at higher speeds
Blocked drain holes can cause internal water damage
expertReviews.verdict: The NB generation MX-5 (1998-2005) delivers the purest driving experience of any MX-5, achieving Mazda's Jinba Ittai philosophy better than any other car. While not fast on paper, it excels at making driving feel engaging and fun. The main concern is rust, particularly in structural areas, but clean examples offer exceptional value. This is arguably the sweet spot MX-5 - more refined than the NA but retaining the pure driving essence that later generations diluted.

expertReviews.title: An Old Miata is the Best Project Car | 2001 Mazda MX-5 ...
pros: Excellent modifiability and project car potential
Good handling with independent suspension front and rear
Lightweight at 2200-2300 lbs
Four-figure price tag makes it affordable
Well-designed 1.8L engine that's easy to work on
Good visibility and balanced road feel
Strong aftermarket support for modifications
cons: Poor wind noise especially with soft top up
Limited power from 1.8L engine (143 hp)
Suspension and components show wear after 22 years
High seating position feels awkward
Only 4.5 cubic feet of trunk space
Automatic transmission not ideal for sports car
expertReviews.verdict: The 2001 Mazda MX-5 Miata NB is an excellent project car and affordable entry into sports car ownership. While it shows its age with worn suspension and limited power, its lightweight design, excellent modifiability, and four-figure pricing make it a great canvas for customization. Whether keeping it stock or heavily modifying it, this Miata offers tremendous potential and value for enthusiasts.

expertReviews.title: Why would you NOT buy a Mazda NB MX-5/Miata? Detailed ...
pros: Resilient interior that doesn't get brittle like NA generation
Post-update models have improved fit and finish with less rattles
Most powerful MX5 ever built (SP turbo version)
Superior paint quality compared to NA and ND generations
Very supportive owner community and forums
Easy DIY repairs with basic tools
Decent ergonomics even for taller drivers
cons: Rust issues in cold climates especially around seals and wheel arches
Soft top only lasts 10-15 years if neglected
Roof can leak through failed rain rails or blocked drainage
Some parts becoming expensive and rare (carbon fiber airbox $3000)
Lacks charm of NA pop-up headlights and modernity of ND
Least aggressive looking of all MX5 generations
Power windows may slow down with age
Metal interior trim pieces can go missing on SP models
expertReviews.verdict: The NB MX-5 is a solid middle generation that improved interior quality and reduced rattles compared to the NA, but lacks the distinctive character of other generations. While rust and aging soft tops are concerns in harsh climates, Australian cars should be relatively trouble-free. The rare SP turbo version commands premium prices up to $50,000. For most buyers, post-update Series 2-4 cars offer the best balance of features and reliability.
